ADDITIONAL_INFORMATION: The significant quantity changes from prior years’ reports in Sections B.1, B.3, and B.4 reflect the results of service line data updating initiatives in 2021 which also allowed moving to a GIS-based accounting method for the DOT Report that better captures known and verified assets. This explains the increase in total service count (including a large drop in steel service counts and a large increase in plastic service counts), increase in "other" material types, drop in average service length, changes in the size ranges, increases in unknown size steel and PE, increase in PE services less than 1", as well as the increase in older decades-of-installation from the 2020 DOT report to the 2021 DOT report.
The previously submitted report incorrectly had higher leak counts in Part C due to some leaks being miscategorized as reportable PHMSA leaks.

The significant quantity changes from prior years’ reports in Section B.1 reflects the results of service line data updating initiatives in 2021 which allowed moving to a GIS-based accounting method that better captures known assets. This explains why all of these bare steel counts have been significantly reduced or eliminated (for CP-protected and CP-unprotected) and moved into the coated categories. Section B.3 and B.4 reflect the combined impacts of: (1) another serviceline data clean-up initiative, as well as (2) a related change of approach in the serviceline counting method for the DOT Report. The serviceline data clean-up initiative here in focus was a project to digitize service lines in GIS, based on active meter locations, where servicelines are known to exist and not already digitized but have minimal installation records. The related change in counting method was a shift to reporting service lines entirely out of GIS using known and verified assets. The combined impact of these on serviceline reporting explains the increase in "other" material type, increase in PE services less than 1", changes in the size ranges, increase in average service length, as well as the increase in older decades-of-installation from the 2020 DOT report to the 2021 DOT report.

Transporter is Mississippi Natural, Inc along a 6.5 mile 8" steel gas pipeline from the Gulf South inlet. Operations Mgr for Mississippi Natural is Trent Johnson. (3)Odorization for gas is by Mississippi Natural at the inlet per Gulf South with the King Tool 1-B with an 6 5/8" outlet and holds 2.2 gallons of odorant with an odorant reserve tank that contains 55 gallons. It's maximum capacity is 150,000 SCFH. The WLNG (in-house) system is tested each month by New Style Odorant from Heath Consultants. Any abnormal reading over 1.00 would be discussed with Mississippi Natural. They would make the proper adjustments at their injection site. Other corrosion area inside Mississippi Natural regulator station is for WLNG 2 key valves and they were repainted in early 2021 and were ok.
